text: i bought this sweatshirt in dc, in may- before families were being separated and detained at the border and before living the nightmare that has been the confirmation hearing for #brettkavanaugh - the sign outside the shop said “gifts for your “woke grad” -funny and cool.  but how naive i was.  i thought that going to the women’s march and other protests and wearing my pussy hat was fun and exciting- almost that feeling of our generation finally something to fight for.  never thinking that we actually need to fight for our rights.  i wore the sweatshirt this morning and young white woman stopped me in back bay station at the height of the commuter rush and said politely , “can i just say i love your shirt ?” i smiled and said thank you.  i didn’t think anything of it and certainly didn’t imagine that it would elicit the kind of response that compels a stranger to stop you or talk to you.  next up - the airport security line, a young black tsa male officer, checking my id, said i like your shirt and i said i’m a thoughtful woman worried about our rights and he said we need that right now and as i walked away, he persisted, we need that right now.  while i waiting to go the through the scanner, i saw a 2 white women struggling with a 10 year old boy who’s crying, panicking, trying to run through the line and he attacked and hit a black female tsa officer, who remained calm throughout the ordeal.  the women caring for the child appeared to be trying the best could to manage the situation.  when i get to the line to be screened, a middle-aged white male tsa officer says to the man in front of me, “i would hate to be on a flight with that kid, they oughta sedate him.” and before i could process that compassionless and uneducated comment, it was my turn and he says, “i don’t agree with your shirt” and as is fucking typical, i wish i had said, which part don’t you agree with? women uniting ? or that we can, and should be nasty?  but i just stuck with what i said before, i’m a thoughtful woman worried about our rights.  he said he liked that better, more diplomatic.  therein lies the problem- i’m trying to voice my opinion but why i am trying to be so pleasing ?

text:
this photo really touched my heart.  i was recently asked why i didn’t tell earlier, by someone who does not really understand the millions of reasons we can’t tell. my first reaction was shame. and then i remembered, wait a minute. firstly i was 4 years old. that set me up for a future of fear. then when i was 12 and it was someone other than my father and uncle, i did tell. i was called a liar by his sister and the rest of the church members. so without making this a one sided issue, i just wanted to say, there is a lot of hurt, a lot of shame and a lot of unresolved anger floating around right now. compassion is what i feel for so many suffering. so many just trying to make it through one day of not feeling the pain. and compassion for those that truly don’t understand those millions of reasons. i hope the awareness and education continues.  rant over 💜
#stopsexualabuse 
#courageoussurvivors
#dontexpectmetocry
#metoo
#whyididntreport

text_retweet:
#repost @time
• • •
when dr. christine blasey ford walked in to face the senate judiciary committee on sept. 27, raised her right hand and swore to tell the truth, it was clear that an unassuming psychology professor and mother of two was about to change the course of current events in real time. “i am here today not because i want to be,” ford said to senators, who were prepared to assess her allegation that judge brett kavanaugh had sexually assaulted her some 36 years ago, a charge he vigorously denies. “i am terrified.” at stake was a potential lifetime appointment to the #supremecourt that could change decades of legal rulings and affect the nation’s faith in its judiciary. the hopes and fears of #women and men who have lived with the trauma of sexual violence were riding on the credibility of ford’s testimony. by the time the hearing ended, ford had done more than prove herself a credible witness. women called into c-span to tell their own, decades-old stories of harassment and rape. #whyididntreport exploded on social media, a rallying cry for those who had never gone public about their own sexual assault until then. ford’s testimony slowed the machinery of political power when it was fully in gear. an npr/pbs newshour/marist poll released oct. 3 found that 45% of respondents thought ford was telling the truth, compared to 33% who believed kavanaugh. ford’s testimony may not prevent kavanaugh’s confirmation. but it was a powerful warning that wealth, status and a record of professional accomplishments were no longer enough to override credible allegations of sexual assault, no matter when they occurred. to young #men, it was a message that drunken violence could shadow them. to victims, ford’s testimony was an invitation to speak up, no matter how powerful the accused, no matter how long ago the attack. people will listen, the country seemed to reassure them. we will believe you.

text:
we see you 
trading your compassion for your “power” 
trading your humanity 
to sustain the lie that everything’s okay 
to sustain the lie that you are holding it together 
but we see you broken 
unfeeling in this 
concealing with this 
acting out your wounds
unleashing your pain

how small must you be 
that you would build victories
on the backs of victims

how small must you be 
that you would refuse to see us

as we simply ask you 
to see yourselves 
how have you become so broken? 
no matter what they do

nothing will change the fact that even in this 
we have learned to better see ourselves and each other

to realize that we are one of too many 
to realize that broken people will never make us whole 
to realize that it was never our fault

we were never to blame

and even if we aren’t believed 
we will be heard

our courage will be felt

instructive in its clarity

that we deserve so much more than this

unwavering in its belief 
that we will be the alchemists 
that this will end with us

read “and even if we aren’t believed” on the @makedaband site. #linkinbio

text: decades before #metoo and the current equal pay for equal work push, this woman, my mom, was thrown into cook county jail to investigate inmates getting pregnant while incarcerated. she was able to go undercover, because she had previously been working as a news reporter on the radio, and the general public was unfamiliar with her appearance. after several days in jail, she was released and despite contracting amoebic dissentary while incarcerated, she completed her first on camera report as an investigative journalist. that led to several decades as “on air” talent, from reporter to anchor and editorial director, that culminated with numerous emmy nominations, 5 emmy wins, numerous group emmys, over 100 awards for excellence, including best commentary in the nation awarded from american women in broadcasting, presented to by barbara walters and jane paulette in new york city. she did all this while women were at bet considered 2nd class citizens. happy birthday mom. i couldn’t be more lucky to have you as a mom. i love you.
name: Tom McComas

text:
so what is sexual wholeness exactly? and wtf is an empowered creatrix? ✨
glad you asked!
✨
this intra-post-#metoo culture in which we find ourselves offers a smorgasbord of questions and options, but few definitive answers as of yet. we as women find ourselves speaking up and speaking out more than ever, but then what? what happens after we share our story? what happens after we open that can of worms? how do we honor our stories without allowing them to become bigger than we are? how do we evolve?
✨
having voiced my own #metoo story for 33 of my 36 years, i’ve sought the answers to these questions my entire life. and now i’m excited. really excited. because now it seems everyone is asking the same damn questions. ✨
so i created this: a workshop that seeks to hone together the embodiment of sexual wholeness and the practice of experiencing ourselves as powerful creatrix. we are productive in our places of healing. out of our stories come action. we are pragmatically greater, not lesser, for our various traumas. ✨
expect lecture, a therapeutic yoga practice that borrows from the yin and kundalini lineages, some somatic breathwork, and a profound meditation to help you dig deeper in the most powerful of ways. please bring something to write with and on.
✨
i look forward to seeing all of you!
:

text:
i have said it before and ill say it again books teach us something.  with all the current events surrounding entitlement, sexual assault, the me too movement and ramifications this actions have on us all we need to sit down with friends and family and have a conversation.  talk to our boys/men tell them that its coolee to be the good guy, the friend, the respectful one than the big man on campus. speak to our girls/women and remind them its ok to flirt, to have fun but always be aware of your surroundings.  safety in numbers on both sides.  and if you see someone in trouble or putting themselves in that situation like the country song says: take a drunk girl home.  to me the three best novels on this subject are: it happens all the time by amy havatny, everything we ever wanted by emily giffin and testimony by anita shreve.  if anything these novels will leave an emotional impact and hopefully start some talk.  lets start a society where its cool to be the nice guy and girls can use their voices!! as an aside all these novels are seared into my brain and heart. i love talking about them and are avaliable for sale at barnes and noble in wilmington. @bnwilmington come see me and talk about it

#metoo #talkaboutit #booksthatmatter

text:
“the past few weeks have brought up a lot of emotions in me, including anger. in my 20s i was raped. and since then i have been groped and aggressively sexually harassed multiple times. and yes i remember the minute details of how the attacks felt – particularly the mocking refusal to stop. but i do not remember the name of the street, the exact date and time. there were no witnesses and i did not report. “what would happen,” i asked myself then. no one would get caught, nothing would change, i would just sit and be scrutinized in a police station for hours, bare myself, feel mortified, and that would be that. so i didn’t report then. but the #metoo movement and talking to survivors of violence at women for women international compelled me to share my story last year and to continue to do so.” -laurie adams, women for women international ceo

read the rest of laurie’s blog on our website. link in bio.

text:
call your senators
tel:202-224-3121
because i #believechristine i #believesurvivors and i #believewomen
because i don’t want someone who goes on wildly partisan rants, who is contentious and belligerent, and who lies under oath to serve as a judge on the highest court in this country.
because i don’t want a member of #scotus who does not believe that an impartial judiciary should be a check on presidential power, or that does not believe a sitting president can be indicted.
because i don’t want a supreme court justice who would threaten rights & protections for reproductive freedom.
because i don’t want a supreme court justice who prioritizes corporate interests over public health and the environment. 
most of all, because if we don’t heed the claims of #drchristineblaseyford we insult all of us who can say #metoo all of us with a litany of reasons for #whyididntreport and anyone who has ever been silenced, overlooked, or othered in any way while a white man gets a pass for bad behavior and ascends to a position of power. we can not continue to normalize this behavior. 
thank you @time and @zenpop for making this the cover.

text: combining their talents in photojournalism and writing, wong may-e and kristen gelineau pack a powerful punch at objectifs' exhibition "women in film & photography". their annotated body of work investigates the impact of ethnic cleansing against the rohingyas in myanmar, provoking us to care, and to take a stand on violence against women in war. using the eyes as a two-way window into their subjects' experience and their audience's hearts, may-e and kristen's work captures our gaze, attention, and empathy. still focused on the rohinyas' plight hours later, i wonder "will i ever be able - and should i be permitted - to simply look away?" exhibition runs until 18 november 2018. image credit: wong may-e #objectifssingapore #womenphotographers #metoo #singaporeexhibition  #singaporeart #photographyexhibition

text:
my dog jasmine is 12 years old this year. when we compare or see her with other dogs her age she seems a little younger.  she has good energy still, she wags her tail a lot, and she loves to go on walks and even runs a little.  she seems like she’s in a pretty good positive mood most of the time. i think we can take some helpful ideas from jasmine, and other beings, human and not, who are able to transcend society’s ideas about time and aging.  incorporating some or all of these every day will help you feel young on the inside, and not that it really matters on a soul level, will also translate to looking youthful and glowing on the outside.  just like jasmine.

read jasmine's top tips for staying young at my blog: https://shanaolmstead.com/2018/10/02/how-to-grow-younger-every-day/

text:
quand elle dit non , c’est non .
« au fond de la chambre élégante 
que parfuma son frôlement, 
seule, immobile, elle dégante 
ses longues mains, indolemment.

les globes chauds et mâts des lampes 
qui luisent dans l'obscurité, 
sur son front lisse et sur ses tempes 
versent une douce clarté.

le torrent de sa chevelure, 
où l'eau des diamants reluit, 
roule sur sa pâle encolure 
et va se perdre dans la nuit.

et ses épaules sortent nues 
du noir corsage de velours, 
comme la lune sort des nues 
par les soirs orageux et lourds.

elle croise devant la glace, 
avec un tranquille plaisir, 
ses bras blancs que l'or fin enlace 
et qui ne voudraient plus s'ouvrir,

car il lui suffit d'être belle : 
ses yeux, comme ceux d'un portrait,
ont une fixité cruelle, 
pleine de calme et de secret ;

son miroir semble une peinture 
que quelque vieux maître amoureux
offrit à la race future, 
claire sur un fond ténébreux,

tant la beauté qui s'y reflète 
a d'orgueil et d'apaisement, 
tant la somptueuse toilette 
endort ses plis docilement,

le miroir lui montre, dans l'ombre, 
son amant doucement venu, 
au bord de la portière sombre, 
offrir son visage connu.

elle se retourne sereine, 
dans l'amas oblique des plis, 
qu'en soulevant la lourde traîne 
son talon disperse, assouplis,

darde, sans pitié, sans colère, 
la clarté de ses grands yeux las, 
et, d'une voix égale et claire, 
dit : " non ! je ne vous aime pas. " »
anatole france

text:
content warning: rape
.
i was raped for the first time when i was 14 by a nearly 18 year old. his name was will. he stalked, harassed, & played mind games with me for four years after. his piece de resistance was centered around virginity.
.
will fetishized my virginity. i know it’s one of the reasons he targeted me. i was sweet, soft, guillable, naive, still absolutely a child and “pure.” he spent months priming and grooming me to be “his” and that’s exactly what he thought i would be once he “took” my virginity.
.
somehow will saying “i am jealous colton (my so at the time) will get to “take” your virginity.” “your virginity is a trophy.” “your virginity is the most beautiful gift i wish i could have it.” all this only made me feel a bit uneasy. because i’d been indoctrinated to think these things about my virginity too. i was primed by the religion of my childhood and my cisheteropatriarchal society well before will began grooming me.
.
when will raped me he asked for my consent and then violated it before i even uttered no. when will raped me, to him, he was claiming me as his. he was my first & as he repeatedly told me and tried to enforce - my only. when will raped me he thought he owned me. he made that clear & it damaged my relationship to my body and other people for a decade. when he raped me he showed me the blood on the condom as if to prove i now belonged to him.
.
i fought wild cycles. first, feeling like will owned me as he stalked me & tortured me. then swinging to the opposite extreme engaging in sex & relationships as an act of defiance against will “owning” me. then swinging to shame & resentment. then back to feeling submissive & like his child bride (yea he proposed). over & over till i broke at 18 & finally began healing the damage.
.
the idea that penetrative sex somehow takes your purity, your wholeness. that somehow whoever owns your virginity owns you... it tangibly destroyed me. it’s not just will. it never was. he exploited an oppressive system created by predators to begin with.
.
virginity is a cisheteropatriarchal concept. you can be celibate! your body is yours; but celebrating virginity is oppressive.
.

text:
"i think that it's a very scary time for young men in america when you can be guilty of something that you may not be guilty of," trump said tuesday afternoon outside the white house.
.
back in 1989, trump had no fear of shattering lives. in fact, he led a lynch mob, taking out full page advertisements in every new york paper demanding that the death penalty be applied in the central park jogger case.
.
the nypd had arrested five black or brown children between 14 and 16 to demonstrate speedy progress after a horrific assault that led a young woman fighting for her life. npyd detectives forced confessions, in the absence of lawyers or parents, from 4 of the 5 children.
reflecting on that moment decades later, one of the young boys, yusuf salaam said:
.
“he was the fire starter,” salaam said of trump, in his first extended interview since trump announced his run for the white house. “common citizens were being manipulated and swayed into believing that we were guilty.” — www.theguardian.com/...
.
#yusefsalaam, #kevinrichardson, #koreywise, #antronmccray, and #raymondsantana, the five children who were falsely accused of rape and assault by #donaldtrump were eventually exonerated in 2002. no physical evidence had ever tied them to the victim or the scene, but they’d been convicted nonetheless, on the basis of coerced confessions extracted by an out of control and inept nypd. over a decade after their convictions, dna evidence implicated a known sex offender. nypd detectives had botched the case and let a dangerous rapist roam free for years. the city paid tens of millions in a settlement to the central park five, who spent most of their youth behind bars on false charges.
.
the five children spent between 5 and 15 years in jail. their lives were shattered by donald trump, his ego, and his #racism. he was the fire starter.
.

text:
triggered by the news? here’s what you can do:
with the investigation into the allegations against judge brett kavanaugh, hearing dr. ford’s testimony, and because of the openness of the #metoo movement, women are talking now more than ever about how they are “triggered”.
.
we’d like to take this opportunity to help you more greatly understand triggers, to best navigate your emotions and how you respond to others around these important and difficult issues.
.
so, what is a “trigger” and what does it mean to “be triggered”?
a trigger is an event, including even a thought, that sets off a memory or set of memories and painful feelings associated with a trauma.
.
this is different from being upset, or even angry, about what is happening. understanding this difference can help you respond and support yourself and others in the best way.
.
if you are triggered, and have symptoms of post traumatic stress disorder (ptsd), you should get help from professionals who treat ptsd. it is our, and many others' opinions, that while medication can reduce some of the symptoms, it does not heal ptsd, which is a psychological disorder.
.
doug and i help people heal from trauma and ptsd, and this often involves helping to release the trauma from the body. we also often refer people for emdr treatment.
.
if you or someone you know needs immediate help, please contact the national sexual assault hotline: 1-800-656-4673
.
you can learn more about how to work with your triggers to help you heal from your past traumas through our ceh online workshop - your triggers are a gift: from reactive to empowered: link in bio.
.

text:
per fox news: “‘sasse, from nebraska, didn’t reveal who he asked trump to nominate but did hint it was a woman. ...
“part of my argument then was that the very important #metoo movement was also very new and this senate is not at all well prepared to handle potential allegations of sexual harassment and assault that might have come forward,” sasse said, adding his warning “was absent of knowing a particular nominee.”...
“we all know that the president cannot lead us through this time,” sasse said in his emotional speech.’”
unequivocally, sen. sasse, that is a fail. 
genuine leaders take an oath and make a path, they do not take a path directed by fear of what a triggered group of people think about it.
he continued:
“i believe we have a widespread legacy of sexual assault in this country,” sasse said.
of this, he is correct. it includes males and females of all ages in all stages of life. it is pure evil.
although the daily routine rape of taxpaying american voters simply doesn’t compare in the least, the indignation by failed leadership is real. 
recognize that the point of inertia we face is crucial. the wins sustaining liberty at this time are critically necessary. 
support your president, sen. sasse. history has been smiling lately if you’ve been looking broadly enough.
✨⚖️✨🇺🇸✨⚖️✨
#liberty #victory #scotus #maga #sooth #crisis #freedom #justice #bench #history #historical #republic #win #responsibility

text_retweet:
i relate to what she wrote here about being taught silence and not to be inconvenient and take up too much space. thankfully, once i moved to nm in my mid twenties, i started to unlearn these behaviors that were forced upon me by bio fam who didn’t want to deal with their own shit, by society....these days have been triggering for me...and i’m gearing up to write about it, but i’m also busy with the good things in my love, things i brought in my unlearning and breaking the chain and the cycles of abuse whenever possible. @therealalexandrabillings, thank you for your words. # #repost @lavernecox with @get_repost
・・・
with everything going on in our politics this is what i needed to read today.................................................................................................................@regran_ed from @therealalexandrabillings -  i was raped in an alley in 1983 by a man who attacked me from behind and then ran off. 
i remember when i was being chased through the park by an abusive lover and when i saw a police car at a stop light, i screamed for help. they saw me, pointed, laughed and drove off. being transgender was a joke and a crime and asking for help was futile
so i didn’t
and throughout my life, since i can remember, i was taught silence. not to get too loud. not to make too much noise. and not to to take up too much space. my problems were mine and didn’t need to be shared and so my shame became my home and my soul became barren. 
so i never reported what happened to me. but just because i never reported it, doesn’t mean it didn’t happen 
i am whole now. i am healing now. i am surrounded by those who didn’t make it, who didn’t survive and i am held by those who did. and so my heroes live in all kinds of bodies and continue on in the stories we tell. 
and there are still those of us who are silenced and so our job is to be with them. our job is to stay present.

text:
«очень боялась подцепить какую-нибудь заразу». роналду обвиняют в изнасиловании
.
приготовьтесь – вас ждёт пикантное чтиво.
.
криштиану роналду обвиняют в изнасиловании американской модели кэтрин майорги, которое якобы имело место в 2009 году в лас-вегасе. сразу после инцидента девушка подала заявление в полицию, не называя при этом имени насильника. но через год подписала договор с юристами роналду о неразглашении информации, получив за это $ 375 тыс.
.
о деле все успели забыть, но в 2017 году издание der spiegel опубликовало расследование, в котором подробно излагались события той самой ночи в лас-вегасе. а осенью этого года выступила сама девушка: под хештегом #metoo жертвы сексуального насилия делились своими историями в социальных сетях, и кэтрин не осталась в стороне.
.
в итоге полиция лас-вегаса возобновила расследование
.
#лас-вегас #кэтрин #der #spiegel #роналду #изнасилование

text:
what a fucking few weeks. it’s enough to make a girl want to – ugh, i don’t even know anymore. i feel like i’m one on on one of those playground spinny things that is moving at warp speed, and i can’t seem to jump off. you, too?

feeling a strong need for my sisters today, and to be reminded that we’re all going through this together.

so, my treasured friends, if you’ve been feeling inexplicably tender or weepy or cynical or ragey or terrified or ragged, like your hormones are on steroids and you’re an over-inflated balloon about to burst any second – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if hearing connie chung’s letter to christine blasey ford this morning made tears leak from your weary eyes – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if hearing donald trump’s disgraceful mocking of dr. ford’s testimony filled your body with a resentment that consumed every raw nerve – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if you’ve been fighting a low-grade pissy-ness at your husband or boyfriend brother boss coworker cousin dad simply because they are men and some men have been shitty to some women – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if you’ve been furious at your friend coworker mother second cousin megyn kelly sarah sanders kellyanne coway because of their inexplicable support for brett kavanagh and anyone else who may ever be accused of sexual harassment/abuse/assault because the victim *might* be lying – it’s okay and you are not alone

if you received the “presidential alert” text yesterday and you cringed and bit back an “under his eye” and wanted to throw your phone into the goddamn toilet – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if you’ve driven your husband off social media with your vigor and volume – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if you alternately or simultaneously want to crawl sobbing under the covers and put on your biggest pair of shit kickers and punch somebody in the throat – it’s okay and you are not alone.

if you’re petrified that the senate isn’t gonna do the right thing and you wonder/hope about what kind of revolt might ensue – it’s okay and you are not alone. if you’re tired of staying quiet and wonder when we’re all gonna start... (cont’d in comments)

text: tw: i'm writing a new #op-ed for the big smoke that johnny letter's "boys will be boys" and rape culture because #metoo #timesup i have been one of the few lucky ones which haven't yet had to face violent rape, and i pray i never will. but i have experienced many other forms of sexual harrassment, coercion, threats, gendered abuse, verbal, emotional, and occasionally physical #abuse (some of which came from a frequent binge drinker who blacked out--i've seen that look of "can't remember, couldn't have done that" panic my whole life, #kavanaugh). i am intimately familiar with how "boys will be boys" becomes your broken other parent becomes you saying "they were just drunk/tired/doesn't-know-what-they-said." i am tired of apologies that are meaningless because they can't remember or accept the results of the behavior that led to those results, again and again and again. i am tired of the free pass offered to people because they are the "breadwinners." nothing ever changes that way. you don't win #bread, you fucking bake it. economic advantage, race, gender, religion, power do not supercede empathy. they do not replace it. so thank you to every #survivor who ever has had the #courage to step forward and point this out at great cost to themselves. thank you to the #trauma warriors who write their poetry and make their art so they can continue feeling love for the world as they work through their pain. thank you to everyone else in this culture who has the courage to take a hard look at ourselves in the mirror and say #ibelieveher and truly thank you to all those who then do the necessary, hard work to make the needed change. #vulnerability #power #vulnerabilityhangover #thankyoudrford #supremecourt #justice #boystomen #accountability #stopkavanaugh #believesurvivors #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawarenessmonth #october #hungryghosts

text:
🇪🇸 yo, hoy, rompo el silencio. los que me conocéis sabéis lo duro que es para mi. porque me toca de cerca, porque lo he vivido, y porque falta concienciación, educación y una ley que ampare a todos los menores que han sido y son abusados sexualmente cada minuto que pasa.
.
rompo el silencio porque ellos y ellas no pueden. porque están asustados, confundidos, amenazados. porque pasa en familias “normales”, porque los principales abusadores están durmiendo en su propia casa. son los propios padres, madres, hermanos, primos, amigos... .
.
#rompoelsilencio porque no quiero que le pase a nadie más. me uno a @savethechildren_es con la esperanza de que juntos logremos que la ley cambie. las víctimas tienen que convivir con ello de por vida... cómo es posible entonces que, para la ley, una atrocidad así prescriba?!.
.
rompe el silencio tu también por todos aquellos que no pueden hacerlo y reclama medidas contra el abuso sexual infantil, comparte en redes sociales, difunde entre tus amigos. no caigas en la trampa de pensar que esto no te puede pasar a ti, porque a mi me pasó..
.
🇬🇧 today i break the silence. for those who know me, this is a really hard thing for me to do. i do it because it’s close to my heart, because it has happened in my own home and mainly because there’s a lack of awareness, education and laws that protect all minors that have been or are being sexually abused right now. .
i break the silence because they can’t talk. because they’re kids and they are afraid, confused, threatened. because it happens in “normal” families, because the abusers are mainly family members who sleep in the room next door. because it’s the father, the mother, the brother, the cousin...
.
i break my silence because i don’t want this to happen to anybody else. i join @savethechildren with the hope that together we can make the law change. atrocities like this can’t prescribe, because the victims have to survive it every day!.
.
please share, talk about it, raise awareness and help victims of sexual abuse. don’t make the mistake of thinking this can’t happen to you, because it happened to me.
#sexualabuse #vanlifediaries #reallifeshit #vanlife #projectvanlife #openingup
name: Dog in a van

text:
all the feels this last week culminating into a break down last night with tears and floods of memories i’d prefer not to have resurface. how many times will it take for a woman to share for men to finally listen? how long will it take for the belief that “boys will be boys” to die? when will people start believing what women say without needing a play by play? and if a white woman’s words are not heard when is there hope for a woman of color’s words to be heard?

we have to do better, we must. every day that my son’s world expands i must teach him daily that being a white male comes with an unspoken privilege that does not mean he should ever act in that privilege to his benefit. every day i must teach him the power of consent through my actions, words and example. every day i must teach him to respect and honor those different from him and to learn the power of empathy, true empathy. and every day i simultaneously need to teach my daughter to protect, guard and prepare for what she’s up against in a world of white men who’s words are seen as more than hers. i need to teach her to acknowledge her worth from within and her power from within. after all we all are mother or babies - women always truly hold the power as we have the power to birth and give life. and i need to teach her to listen when she is the one in privilege. 
when will this change? i sure as hell hope it’s in my children’s lifetime, but the hope is weaning. .
.
.
.
#metoo #motherhood #vote #mothersofboys #mothersofdaughters #bethechange

text:
#tbt it took a crane to get this mamma and baby in! we lurv this design classic so dang much. did you know that italian architect and designer gaetano pesce’s iconic “up5” chair and “up6” ottoman was a feminist statement piece? a man well ahead of his time and the #metoo movement,  pesce was inspired by the silhouettes of fertility goddesses and the attached ottoman represents a ball and chain. #throwbackthursdays .
“it’s an image of a prisoner,” pesce says. “women suffer because of the prejudice of men. the chair was supposed to talk about this problem.”.... and .... “i was telling a personal story about my notion of women: despite themselves, women have always been prisoners of their own making.”
.
dayum!! that’s deep! and prescient when applying this theory to our current times and issues. 
not to mention the chair is one of the most comfortable we’ve ever sat in.  #gaetanopesce #studiollondon .
.
.
#designicon #bebitalia #up5 #up6 #70sfurniture #feminist #genius #legendary  #concept #deepthoughts #architect #productdesign #italiandesign

text:
as both a survivor myself and a clinician, the past several weeks have been especially tough. i do my best to be a mindful consumer of news around kavanaugh’s hearing, yet i also treat trauma and ptsd. many of my clients are sexual assault survivors, and the news either exacerbates their pain, or reopens old wounds. if there’s one thing i hope people are taking away from this storm, it’s that sexual assault is insanely common. in any given room of people, you can bet that you’re in a room with at least one survivor (and probably more than one).
-
💞
i wanted to share some tips for handling ptsd when the news re-triggers you or intensifies your recovery process. i’ve also linked in my bio to a fantastic medium article full of resources. check it out, and feel free to share more tips in the comments below.
-
💞
the hashtag #whyididntreport is a powerful one, but please remember that survivors are not required to be advocates. sharing your story is one of many ways to heal, and you never have to share what you’ve been through to make it more valid. lots of people heal best through public expression of their pain, and plenty others prefer to heal privately. -
💞
sending 💛healing vibes💛 to all of you today.

text_retweet:
🤬🤬🤬#repost @afrogirlfitness with @repostapp
・・・
this is both saddening and infuriating .
via: @sheisestella i personally witnessed the death of a black mother who delivered twins by c-section. she was groaning loudly (as you would when you're in pain) in the ward for over an hour while nurses and midwives carried on with their duties; turning a blind a eye to her.
i had also delivered my first son by c-section on the same day and was brought to the icu (intensive care unit) where i watched the incident unfold from across the room. 
after an hour or more of consistent groaning and slithering on her bed, alarms signalled and our room curtains were speedily drawn to close while she was taken away by emergency staff. a midwife later made known to us that she'd passed away.
this incident affected me massively. i carried a lot of fear and anxeity during my week stay at the hospital and in my subsequent pregnancies; all as a result of the incident. .
#blackmothers #blacklivesmatter #metoo #serenawilliams #afrogirlfitness

why do most films portray women purely as love interests? why do women not have their own story arcs, goals and lives? why do women characters exist purely to fulfil men’s romantic plot lines? #unstereotypecinema with @oxfam_india

in a study that surveyed over 45 mainstream hindi films, it was found that only 23% of films had lead roles are played by female characters. in 76.7% of films women fulfil a romantic function, either as a co-lead in a romantic role (37.2%) or as a romantic interest (38.5%). including those in lead roles, about 48% of women were found to make some contribution in moving the plot. however, in about 2/3 of films, the plot movers do so driven by revenge, retribution against violence and by playing a romantic role. men dominate the narrative, playing the lead role in 77% of films. ✊🏼 curated stories on #feminism

text:
love @mindcharity and there new #asktwice campaign.  one in four of us will suffer a mental health problem in our lifetime and the stigma that’s still very much prevalent around mental health means that so many people don’t ask for the help they need when they need it,  that or usually roll out the same old line “i’m fine” when asked if their ok.  if you notice a change in someone and think it may be mental health related ask if their ok, they’ll probably tell you their fine, but just to be sure...ask again, the second time they may just reveal the truth!

text:
stole this from a friend’s post, but i felt compelled to share!
****************************************
peter and i discussed yesterday how with all of the backlash the #metoo movement is getting, there seems to be this gaping hole where empathy for others used to be. people seem to be so worried about picking sides, they are not stopping to think through what another person may be going through on the inside, which makes me feel sad and scared. scared that if this path we’ve started down as a society continues, then where will we be 5, 10, or 15 years from now? compassion for others is a huge part of what makes us human, in my opinion. what can you do today to show compassion for another, and try to think through what their perspective may be before reacting negatively?
#socialworkerrant #compassion #empathy #understandingothers #alloftheallegedvictimscantbelying

text:
"my sexuality: from conflict to ownership" ▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️▫️
i was teased and called names in school…‘chakka’, ‘koja’, ‘ombodh’. i realised in my early teens that i was gay. i didn’t want to be gay because of the teasing. i remember sitting up on the terrace many times, looking up at the sky and asking god to stop making me gay. i became depressed few years after that. there were many days where all i have done isjust walk around. i was even suicidal, twice i almost killed myself. but reading about sexuality and a series of videos on youtube helped me become better.

around the time i started college was when i was finally okay, i had come out to a lot of people regarding my sexual orientation. i was in a place where i was owning my sexuality. that’s when i also started queer campus with my friend. but i had moved to a new place for college. here again, i felt like i had to go back to the closet. i didn’t want to be an easy target for ragging. i was in a bad place again. for the first time in my life, i was having anxiety, panic attacks and i wouldn’t be able to breathe properly. shutting down my sexuality really affected my mental state.

continued...

.

text: exactly. this is why we say it’s all the same divine feminine energy-the earth and the women. once there was a time when both were honored and revered, respected and appreciated. it was not always a patriarchy that devalues life givers and sucks the earth dry of her resources. it was not always a world where males were elevated and in control while women were silenced and bullied, where the earth is poisoned. the great reckoning that is occurring now is simultaneously about the voice of women and the rights of the planet; the elements, the animals and the plants. patriarchy is a virus which infects all in its way, our men are sick with it even as the worst of the illness hurts the earth and her daughters. the toxic, imbalanced form of masculine energy that has dominated for a long time is killing us all as it has devalued that which gives life. if you believe in protecting the water you must also protect those who create life inside the water in our bodies, and if you believe in protecting your wives, mothers, sisters, daughters, you must also stand for the conscious life force of mother earth.

awareness is necessary!  @theebutterflyproject has been dropping knowledge and i'm here for it.  i will be sharing the information they provide because someone needs it. 
let's stand together! 💜  follow their page!

#repost @theebutterflyproject (@get_repost)
・・・
most people think abuse is simply being hit. it goes way deeper than physical abuse. most abusers have to get you mentally before physically. would you really let a man hit you just out the clear blue? no, he already started planting seeds in your mind about you doing little things to make him jealous. you're a nobody and you're nothing. he kills your self worth and from their other forms of abuse follow. then there are monitors on your devices or cars. they will use concern to be an abuser as if it is logic to have a tracker on a car. maybe they ration money to you or they make you give them your check. this is abuse. do you feel useless because of words he's said? this is abuse. so rethink, have you been in an abusive relationship? don't judge one because it doesn't look like your situation. we must support one another.
.  #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceadvocates #thebutterflyproject #abusive #abusiverelationship #domesticabuse #domesticviolenceawareness #domesticabuseawareness #stopabuse #theebutterflyproject #domesticviolencesurvivors #metoo #sexualassault #physicalassault #sexualharassment #stopabuse

you are strong. 
you are loved.
you are believed.

text:
jag är så sjukt pepp på att få berätta det här! den 16 oktober släpps "men, masculinity and #metoo", ett arbete som jag lagt ner mycket kärlek på via min tjänst som kommunikatör på män. mina extremt kompetenta kollegor har hjälpt mig skriva denna studie på 52 sidor om hur de nordiska länderna hanterade #metoo, samt hur män reagerade på uppropet. jag har även formgett och illustrerat studien. du kan läsa om huruvida destruktiva maskulinitetsnormer fanns med i debatten kring hur de nordiska länderna jobbat för att aldrig mer behöva ha ytterligare ett #metoo.
som att det inte räcker släpper även @manforjamstalldhet en undersökning utförd av sifo, där vi frågar män hur de ser på sitt ansvar i och med det samhällsproblem som #metoo belyste. jag behöver inte säga hur viktigt det här perspektivet är i debatten. män gör de flesta övergrepp, samtidigt har vi makten att skapa reell förändring. det är snart ett år sedan #metoo krossade tystnadskulturen. vi måste utvärdera! har det blivit någon förbättring?
vi pratar om allt detta, samt premiärar både undersökningen och studien, som du får med dig hem i tryckt form, på ett frukostseminarium den 16 oktober! anmäl dig via länk i min bio så kan vi hälsa på varandra 👋 🤗✨
ovan ser du små snippets av studien. fet pepp-kram! ❤️
#metoo #maskulintansvar #machokultur #eftermetoo

text:
for the past couple of months, i have taken a step out of the political world. i recently graduated with my bachelors in political science but decided to take a step back because of the overwhelming stress i felt and continue to feel during this administration. yesterday, i watched a video of donald trump shame, question, and ridicule a survivor of sexual assault. i came to tears at my office desk. when people especially people in positions of authority and influence,question and mock victims, it creates a dangerous environment for victims everywhere. watching the president of my country say those things only makes me feel shame. so yes, i will continue to say donald trump is not my president because i refuse to be shamed for something that was not my fault. the past two months i have reclaimed my sexuality, reclaimed my voice, and reclaimed my body. i will continue to survive by not being guilted or ridiculed by weak men. #metoo
—————————————————————

text:
you are not alone

colleen' story: 
i have battled anxiety, depression and overcome anorexia. what got me through my pain is putting purpose to my pain. i ended up writing and recording an album with a sound engineer of my songs sharing my journey through song. i dedicated the album to sufferers of mental illness. it was the scariest thing i ever did but through it, i found my authentic voice:  a voice that is vulnerable, but even more so, one that's brave. my message is that we are all brave, worthy of being seen and heard, and that our scars and pain eventually turn to gold and become our strength.
@serenity_words_for_the_soul 
just want to say a massive thank you for your bravery in sharing this. if any of you want to contribute your story, please send me a dm, i would love to hear from you. i think it's so important that we all learn to be open about our struggles because 
a) it helps others realise that they are not alone
b) it helps others understand what it's like to suffer from mental illness
c) it normalises mental illness, reducing the stigma and consequent shame

text:
grateful to donate this painting for auction for a great organization and gala this evening! 
healing the voice within is a one-of-a-kind art fundraiser that gives voice and healing to those traumatized by childhood sexual abuse, and will help raise awareness and much-needed funds for important initiatives at the gatehouse. 
the gatehouse is a safe place for children to disclose abuse to police and child welfare workers, as well as a support network for adult survivors of childhood sexual abuse.  as a part of the healing process, the gatehouse offers a comforting healing atmosphere for toronto police and other child welfare organizations to conduct interviews with children and their families. 
1 in 3 girls and 1 in 5 boys will be sexually assaulted at some time in their lives.

https://www.canadahelps.org/en/charities/the-gatehouse-child-abuse-investigation-support-site/events/healing-the-voice-within-2/

this painting reflects on my own personal accounts of sexual abuse. it was painted while i lived in florence. lets keep talking about this and helping those around us any way we can.

text:
journal entry october 3, 2018—
i haven’t written in almost a month. it’s not like i have had much to say, if anything there’s been a lot on my mind, too much to say. i didn’t/don’t even know where to start.
rape has been a huge strong topic all over this month. and how i sometimes feel i need to share my story, but i’ve been scared to.
i don’t want to share to receive attention or sympathy, just to let other women and girls know that they’re not alone. we don’t need to feel guilt or shame for what’s happened to us. but we do need to speak the fuck up and say no more.
sometimes i’ve compared my story to others, and feel like my story isn’t enough to share, like it could’ve been worse. they were or had been my boyfriends at the time, how does that count as rape? news flash, it does. you didn’t want it? you didn’t ask for it? it’s rape.
.
the last time i had sex was back in january, and it was because my ex boyfriend had raped me.
we had gotten together to catch up. i had invited him back over to my place; which i shouldn’t have done. he took that as his “invitation” to get me in bed.
i remember we were drinking a beer, talking in my kitchen and he tried to kiss me and touch me. i said no, more than once.  but he kept pushing and said “you know you want to”. the more he tried, the more i kept telling him no. i told him to stop and that he needed to leave. but he wasn’t going anywhere, not until he got what he wanted. he picked me up and tried to carry me into my room. i grabbed onto the door frame trying to stop him, i was trying to climb over and off of him like i was a monkey. for him it seemed to be all fun and games.
after struggling to not let him take me i couldn’t any longer and he proceeded to take me to my room where he pull down my pants.
i just wanted it to be over as quick as possible while i covered my face trying to hold back sobs and tears.
once it was over i let him out and have not seen him since.
he’s tried to reach me a few times. the first i responded and told him i wanted nothing to do with him ever again and to not reach me. i didn’t respond to the texts that came after that.
his last text was in april.
.
continued in comments-

text:
on wednesday, connie chung published a letter to christine blasey ford, who alleges that supreme court nominee brett m. kavanaugh sexually assaulted her when they were in high school, in @washingtonpost. in the letter, the broadcast journalist describes her own experience with sexual assault. “dear christine blasey ford,” chung writes. “i, too, was sexually assaulted — not 36 years ago but about 50 years ago. i have kept my dirty little secret to myself.”
•
while the “exact date and year are fuzzy,” chung writes, the details of what happened “are vivid — forever seared in my memory.” she goes on to describe the incident and says that she, too, was “terrified” to reveal the story publicly. chung writes: “i wish i could forget this truthful event, but i cannot because it is the truth. i am writing to you because i know that exact dates, exact years are insignificant. we remember exactly what happened to us and who did it to us. we remember the truth forever.” (photo courtesy of connie chung; illustration by @thelilynews)

text:
i bought myself this card when i started doing pottery full time back in 2006. i had no idea what i was doing, only $2000 in savings, and 200 sq. ft. studio (chicken coop) that when it snowed i had to shovel the studio out.
😂 
i want to thank everyone who believed in me, especially when i so desperately wanted to believe in myself. ❤
i had a talk with myself recently about what i could accomplish if i believed in myself as much as others did. 🤔
don't let the self imposed beliefs hold back your greatness!

text:
her
———
on the morning of thursday, september 27th, 2018, an eager anticipation woke us up in our brooklyn loft unusually early. with our hearts racing, we tuned into the hearings of dr. christine blasey ford and judge brett kavanaugh.
———
amidst dr. ford’s emotionally brave testimony, kavanaugh’s flippant denial, and an amalgamation of statements from an assembly of both incredibly compassionate and unbelievably ruthless senators, we made a new song. and it was for her.
———
once the hearings were over, we began putting a video together to more fully capture the inspiration behind this song. we wanted to point to women, from a range of walks of life, women who have taken a stance when it wasn’t necessarily easy to do so. our goal was to highlight the courage it takes to call something out loud and to stand up tall when the odds may not be in our favor.
———
the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric “never look back again” doesn’t imply we shouldn’t look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way — we most absolutely should — but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.
———
see the full video for “her” now! link in bio.
———

video by gracie coates @graciecoates

text:
we owe it to our daughters to raise them as warriors

growing up, i do not recall having hard discussions about sex and intimacy. it was taboo to talk about such things with children, or so it seemed by the lack of conversations on the topic in my household. i am sure i was told not to let anyone touch me in the area where my thighs meet. but there were no tangible speeches about men or boys who preyed on girls. there were no school lessons about pedophiles, rapists or sexual assaulters after snack time. there were no warnings about guys who don’t take no for an answer or that don’t bother asking for permission, especially if they seemed cool. in hindsight, i am unsure if i would have been a raging gutsy feminist had i been, sooner than later, equipped with the knowledge that some men view women as nothing more than objects to be conquered, abused or violated.

gone are the days of cute, brief and awkward exchanges about the birds and the bees. we need ted talks, powerpoints and masterclasses on the dynamics between men and women. i navigated my journey with the opposite sex through trial, error, and silence. it would have been nice to know that i wasn’t alone. the “#metoo movement” exposed stoic suffering in numerous number. but let’s talk about the girls who have never been to hollywood. the little girls who appear to be entirely neglected in this new era of the intolerant “me too.” in light of the latest news cycle and a political rally in mississippi, we need more than a crusade and a hashtag to change the engrained and unchecked demoralizing behaviors our country appears to glorify.

so while we’re still judging women who dare share their stories as if we have permanent appointments on the supreme court, what about the girls? the girls whose relative or family acquaintance made them bear burdens and secrets beyond their years. girls who were urged to greet these same people with a hug or smile every time they visited their homes. and even if she mustered up the fearlessness to tell someone, she would then be asked to forget or pretend it did not happen. (cont.)

text:
you called me pretty and got mad when i told you to leave me alone
angrily, you asked me why i couldn't just 'accept the compliment'

and i thought about the uncle who twirled my hair around his fingers and told me i was pretty
and the boyfriend who pulled down my jeans anyway and told me i was pretty
and the man over the phone
and that guy on my way home from school
and that other someone else i haven't told anyone about yet,

and you wonder why i tried to kill everything pretty about me
why i've taught my back to hunch under unwelcomed gaze
forced this traitorous chest to concave, until all you saw was a cavity
and its funny
because i never wanted to be a hole
to be something you can fill
like those jeans with my ass, said the guys who followed me home from school,
reminding me how much they wanted to take them off

and i wonder
why these genes didn't come with a zipper
why i can't undress myself from this skin
i tried to make my own, but when i unzipped the flesh from my wrist all i found was a warning
a reminder
so forgive me
if i can't just 'accept the compliment'
but from your lips it sounded more like a sentence
like a warning
a reminder
that i have belonged to everyone before myself
and this zipper is just out of my reach
as if to say, 'i'm waiting'
for another someone else 
with chains in their hands
and 'take' on their breath
to come and undress me
to wear me
until i no longer remember what i look like out of this skin
and everything always comes back to this skin
to this 'pretty'
to these genes
that my daughter now wears
praying, 
the day will never come
when another someone else,
will want to put them on
- a.h_blackstone

to wear me
until i no longer remember what i look like out of this skin
and everything always comes back to this skin
to this 'pretty'
to these genes
that my daughter now wears
praying, 
the day will never come
when another someone else,
will want to put them on
- a.h_blackstone

text_retweet:
#repost @time
・・・
when dr. christine blasey ford walked in to face the senate judiciary committee on sept. 27, raised her right hand and swore to tell the truth, it was clear that an unassuming psychology professor and mother of two was about to change the course of current events in real time. “i am here today not because i want to be,” ford said to senators, who were prepared to assess her allegation that judge brett kavanaugh had sexually assaulted her some 36 years ago, a charge he vigorously denies. “i am terrified.” at stake was a potential lifetime appointment to the #supremecourt that could change decades of legal rulings and affect the nation’s faith in its judiciary. the hopes and fears of #women and men who have lived with the trauma of sexual violence were riding on the credibility of ford’s testimony. by the time the hearing ended, ford had done more than prove herself a credible witness. women called into c-span to tell their own, decades-old stories of harassment and rape. #whyididntreport exploded on social media, a rallying cry for those who had never gone public about their own sexual assault until then. ford’s testimony slowed the machinery of political power when it was fully in gear. an npr/pbs newshour/marist poll released oct. 3 found that 45% of respondents thought ford was telling the truth, compared to 33% who believed kavanaugh. that’s a marked shift from 1991, when americans sided with clarence thomas after anita hill accused him of sexual harassment. the facts remain unsettled, and ford’s testimony may not prevent kavanaugh’s confirmation. but it was a powerful warning that wealth, status and a record of professional accomplishments were no longer enough to override credible allegations of sexual assault, no matter when they occurred. to young #men, it was a message that drunken violence could shadow them. to victims, ford’s testimony was an invitation to speak up, no matter how powerful the accused, no matter how long ago the attack. people will listen, the country seemed to reassure them. we will believe you. read this week’s cover story on time.com. illustration by john mavroudis (@zenpop) for time; animation by @brobeldesign

text: this post/babe should really be a #womxncrushwednesday but today is thursday and clinics and deliveries yesterday had us a little overwhelmed. that said this #womxncrushthursday.. is johanna toruno who started @theunapologeticallybrownseries, an ig that celebrates and honours the stories and art of people of colour that have historically rarely been told or honoured as such. scrolling through @unapologeticallybrownseries is a therapeutic foray into beautiful pastel patterns framed with phrases that feel like an activist hug or pat on the back. this post (pictured) really resonated. “thank you anita hill & all of us who have had to go through fires to tell our stories. i stand with those who haven’t & won’t”. coming forward takes courage and anger but outings also can involve privilege of various kinds. we must support each other in the choices we make around reporting. but above all, we must support each other to love our own bodies and soul after experiencing assault. we are important. don’t let anyone, no matter who they are, make you feel otherwise. ❤ #mybodymyrules #selflove #selfcarerevolution #selfcare #love #happy #body #soul #timesup #metoo #metoomovement #whyididntreport #loveyourself #selfloveclub #consent #empowerment #wcw #womancrushwednesday #anitahill

text:
i believe them... because when i was a teenaged college student, i was sexually assaulted by a campus police officer in a patrol car after having gotten into what i was told was 'trouble'. i thought it was my fault. i thought i'd somehow asked for it because i was completely paralyzed with fear and didn't even try and stop him. i really thought that if i said something, people would change my "suspect' title to "gay", and say that i really wanted it.  hell, i'd even convinced myself that i must have wanted it - how else could a 'man' let that happen to him. i remember being confused and afraid while still having to see this person almost daily. i eventually stopped going to classes all together, my grades tanked and i even foolishly "allowed" a 'most likely preventable' car accident to happen just so i didn't have to go back. i disappeared. that part of my life and all the people in it disappeared, and they never even knew why. i wanted to tell someone... anyone, but i couldn't find the words: not even when my parents and professors accused me of just being a bad student and it was the obvious way out (to be fair, they were all confused because i was still very active singing, but that was really just a regular escape from my reality: only other music folks will really get that). i couldn't even tell my favorite aunt, or my close play family. to this day, i don't know why - i just know that i couldn't say the words and make it real. i carried this alone and silently for over 25 years because i didn't know what to do with it.  it's affected me 360 and even worked it's magic in both my personal and professional lives - i've had to shed and heal some mad trust issues, so apologies and love if i ever snapped on or near ya ❤ 
but, not to worry, i've recently gotten the help i needed.  despite this - it still haunts me. and, just like them, the minor, specific details and timelines are mad fuzzy.  but, what's not fuzzy are those 15 mins, exactly how it made me feel and that there's no way the other adults at the time didn't know what that dude was up to. so yeah... i believe every fucking word. #metoo
#ibelievethem
#thisismystory
#findingmypeace

text:
el nuevo diario, nueva york,(efe).- el 5 de octubre de 2017 the new york times destapó el amplio historial de abusos sexuales de harvey weinstein, encendiendo la llama del movimiento #metoo, que cumple mañana su primer año en plena actualidad.

las informaciones del times, de la revista new yorker y de otros medios posteriormente, unidas a los testimonios de víctimas y al poder de las redes sociales, han sacado a la luz un problema que se había mantenido silenciado y han obligado a rendir cuentas a decenas de nombres conocidos de la cultura, la política y los negocios en estados unidos.

hace solo doce meses, weinstein era uno de los hombres más poderosos de hollywood, a pesar de que su actitud con las mujeres era un secreto a voces en el mundillo. hoy, despedido de su propia empresa, está en libertad bajo fianza a la espera de un proceso que podría enviarle durante años a la cárcel.

_
continúa leyendo esta noticia en nuestra página web www.elnuevodiario.com.do

text:
i don't make many political posts, but i have to unleash this rant.
*
the debate about the kavanaugh confirmation hearing is driving me nuts. when i hear the argument that he should be given the job if no one can prove him guilty, it feels like a mockery of our judicial system. it feels like an argument for low standards. this hearing isn't a trial. it's a decision about his ability to be a justice in the supreme court, our highest court, and the last word on critical issues  that move through our court system. supreme court decisions shape legal decisions and set precedents.
*
we should want our supreme court justices to be the people who are most honorable and who will move our country forward while adhering to the law. whether or not anyone can prove the allegations are true is irrelevant at this point. there is a very large difference between "you can't prove it" and "i'm a good person". how he has conducted himself through his confirmation hearing and the number of allegations made by credible people against him prove, if nothing else, that he is of weak moral character and isn't cut out for the job.
*
keep reading below in comments.
*
(photo & poignant satire courtesy of the onion)
.
.
.

text:
wow. i am so honored to bring you this special conversation with a personal heroine, international best-seller, thought leader, and psychotherapist esther perel @estherperelofficial. 🌊
esther’s work practically saved (!!) my relationship with my husband before we got married. her work really helped us see what sustains desire between two people over the long-term, and it's helped us ever since.
💎
this episode is fresh and exciting for a lot of reasons. esther shares how to bring the relational intelligence from our romantic lives (things like trust, empathy, vulnerability, etc) into our most difficult, stressful work relationships and creative collaborations, especially in the context of patriarchy and the #metoo movement. ✨
in fact, i titled the episode "masculinity, power & relationships at work" because we dig into masculinity and how we need to redefine it. esther shares, "all over the world, there have been rituals in all the civilizations where men have to go and make their transition into manhood, to prove that they are real men, to shed the femininity inside of them, the boy inside of them, the weak inside of them...that masculinity therefore is the fragile identity that constantly needs to prove itself and constantly is tested. it doesn’t exist on its own as a solid entity. we need to talk about male power, but i think it’s far more interesting to talk about males feeling of powerlessness. it’s that feeling of powerlessness that turns into control over others." 🔥🔥🔥
what do you think? do you agree? it's ok if you don't! these are conversations meant to generate discussion. ✨
this is a timely conversation that i hope you find helpful and inspiring. 💕 #estherperel #podcast #interview #womeninbiz #womenempoweringwomen #bossbabes 📸 by @juliahembreesmith

text:
if you've experienced/witnessed any abuse in your life then you probably have walked away with some interesting defense mechanisms. those behaviors became your survival mechanisms helping you push forward amidst the confusion and pain and your brain was smart to utilize them. however, they may not be necessary anymore and they may hold you back from fully thriving. it is time to unlearn the abuse and survival tactics! think back on your experiences and look to your behaviors: how were they formed? are they still helpful? would you thrive better without them? i'd love to hear and am happy to help you navigate through unlearning these behaviors! .
.
.
.
.
.
#therapy #erasestigma #mentalhealth #rkarimitherapy #anxiety #depression #positivemind #positivelife #cbt #abuse #defensemechanisims #metoo #believesurvivors

text:
some feminist thoughts to help you unpack the garbage of the kavanaugh debacle in my blog post today. link in profile. 💛

i've got a lot to say on this. to me, this article isn't fully cooked--i don't feel like the flow is quite right. but i do think it's important to get these ideas out there now while and not after all the attention on this issue exists. i've also realized that my hesitance at putting this out there today is itself rooted in my own gendered stuff. my perfectionism and need to have only my best out there is about me not trusting that i have the room to be human, to make mistakes, to put my name on a uncooked article--because i'm already starting with a lack of credibility in the world because of my gender. here's to doing things differently and to putting myself in the conversation despite my imperfections.

text: 🗻the first time i visited the eastern sierras i was in a bad place. the notion of self-care and self-love was a foreign concept to me. 🚫i hadn’t the faintest idea how to be me without someone else. until i took a much needed solo trip to bishop and my first solo hike up to big pine lakes. 🌄it’s here in these mountains, that i was reborn. and every now and then, when life tends to get a little out my control, i pack up my car and head up there to hit the “reset” button. 👆🏻 i cleanse myself of the stressors of the things i cannot change, unburden myself with mistakes i’ve made, and endure the strength i need to keep going. ♥️ these mountains saved my life. these mountains are my paradise. 🏔⛺️

text_retweet:
🙌🏻💜🙌🏻💜🙌🏻. #repost @gracieandrachel with @get_repost
・・・
her
———
on the morning of thursday, september 27th, 2018, an eager anticipation woke us up in our brooklyn loft unusually early. with our hearts racing, we tuned into the hearings of dr. christine blasey ford and judge brett kavanaugh.
———
amidst dr. ford’s emotionally brave testimony, kavanaugh’s flippant denial, and an amalgamation of statements from an assembly of both incredibly compassionate and unbelievably ruthless senators, we made a new song. and it was for her.
———
once the hearings were over, we began putting a video together to more fully capture the inspiration behind this song. we wanted to point to women, from a range of walks of life, women who have taken a stance when it wasn’t necessarily easy to do so. our goal was to highlight the courage it takes to call something out loud and to stand up tall when the odds may not be in our favor.
———
the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric “never look back again” doesn’t imply we shouldn’t look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way — we most absolutely should — but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.
———
see the full video for “her” now! link in bio.
———

———

text:
криштиану роналду обвиняют в изнасиловании американской модели кэтрин майорги, которое якобы имело место в 2009 году в лас-вегасе. сразу после инцидента девушка подала заявление в полицию, не называя при этом имени насильника. но через год подписала договор с юристами роналду о неразглашении информации, получив за это $ 375 тыс.⠀
⠀
о деле все успели забыть, но в 2017 году издание der spiegel опубликовало расследование, в котором подробно излагались события той самой ночи в лас-вегасе. а осенью этого года выступила сама девушка: под хештегом #metoo жертвы сексуального насилия делились своими историями в социальных сетях, и кэтрин не осталась в стороне.⠀
⠀
в итоге полиция лас-вегаса возобновила расследование.⠀
_____________________________________⠀
#роналду #криш #metoo #ювентус #реал #скандал #сексскандал #футболист #криштиануроналду

о деле все успели забыть, но в 2017 году издание der spiegel опубликовало расследование, в котором подробно излагались события той самой ночи в лас-вегасе. а осенью этого года выступила сама девушка: под хештегом  жертвы сексуального насилия делились своими историями в социальных сетях, и кэтрин не осталась в стороне.⠀
⠀
в итоге полиция лас-вегаса возобновила расследование.⠀

text_retweet:
my dear colleague, vicky bellman, in the uk was swifter than i on today's post. here she sums up beautifully what i was also hoping to say today.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
and to her words, i would add - for anyone feeling the sting of the president's behavior - know this: inviting laughter at the expense of another human being in this manner is cruel and is an abuse tactic. we see this and we will not forget. we can and will rise.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#repost @concentriccounselling
.
this was dr ford's response when asked what the most vivid memory was of her experience of assault. her response speaks not only to the humiliation that survivors so often experience, but also to her psychology background, as she references the part of the brain that is responsible for memory storage. for this traumatic experience to then be perpetuated by the president of the united states, at a rally where he mocked her and encouraged the audience to laugh at her, really illustrates why so many victims don't report that experience. i want to see men in power standing up for the experiences of survivors, and passionately and angrily defending their right to safety and respect.
.
in my practice room, i believe survivors. i don't laugh. this isn't funny. and we should all be angry about the culture that has been created, where survivors across the world are being re-traumatised by seeing dr ford mocked by one of the most powerful men in the world.
.
survivors, please know that there are lots of people resisting this culture. lots of people, myself included, who are dedicated to holding safe spaces for your rage, your fear, your grief, and your healing.
.

text:
politics are on my mind these days. i am grateful to dr. christine blasey ford. we individually and the collective of women - assaulted or not we carry trauma in our lineages - are getting triggered to overcome victimhood and to heal. i more than anything want dr. ford to live with a peaceful heart and i’m humbled by her decision to courageously stand strong speaking her truth for all of us. 🙏✨💙🇺🇸 #stopkavanaugh #voiceoftruth #retroactivehealing #drchristineblaseyford #womensupportingwomen #metoo #believewomen #nohate #strength #strongwomen
when watching @michaelmoore’s ”fahrenheit 11/9” last night, reflecting upon the electoral system this indian art print seems most appropriate. 
midst all the chaos in the world, in recent sessions the topic of „being a witness“ came up. here is my suggestion on how to deal with drama that we create or get pulled into (hence it’s also our creation).
when you notice the sensations in your body when breathing steadily and slowly, from your belly into your chest. not trying to change or judge your sensations. becoming aware of how your body responds to what we see, hear, and feel. without judging any of your experience as right or wrong. if you find that you’re doing so, take another deep breath, release the judgements as you exhale, and return to simply observing your experience, inside and out. 
when you practice this, you’re operating from pure awareness, the witness self. it’s the self that feels a deep connection with the world as a participant, while at the same time is centered in the observer. 
operating this way for a few minutes each day becomes a meditation and will stimulate the realization of your connectedness, centered in your heart and soul, allowing you to know your authentic self without attaching concepts about who you are. questions about your life’s purpose in times like this are normal; a reading can help to come back to center.

when you practice this, you’re operating from pure awareness, the witness self. it’s the self that feels a deep connection with the world as a participant, while at the same time is centered in the observer.

#🍄rump isn’t suing anybody. he can’t afford it, haha. 
the new york times on tuesday published a sweeping investigation that documented decades of elaborate, and possibly fraudulent, maneuvering by trump and his family to avoid paying taxes on hundreds of millions of dollars of their wealth. if anything, the article punctures a common myth trump has promoted — that he is a self-made billionaire who started off with “a small loan” from his father, fred c. trump, a new york real estate developer. the story’s headline lays out the essence of the times’s 18 months of digging: “trump engaged in suspect tax schemes as he reaped riches from his father.” story from @washingtonpost ••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••

why womb power? part 2: 
it’s often unconsciously that we, women, men or other are drawn to feminine energy or lifeforce energy, yet its undeniable when it happens -whether it’s from someone, something or through the awe & beauty of nature. by feminine energy i don’t mean a female or a woman specifically as those who’ve experienced it sense that this energy is fluid and life giving-like the womb, thus it’s called “feminine”. don’t be fooled by our pc culture as to the truth of what’s here.

it is time for us womb~men aka wombyn to re-member, honor and cherish own innate power within  our creative center, our inner oracle, our womb-cauldron of life that has all the answers if you stop and listen. 
it is time to come together and stop the b.s.both within ourselves and our collective as women to heal the wounds, own them, support one another in what we each know and have learned and allow what’s highest and best to reveal and from this place, collectively birth a healthier culture from within our own healing work.

text:
@eveensler wrote a beautiful letter in @time magazine, please read. and please (mostly white women), don’t look away and make survivors feel invisible, further adding to their trauma. we can do better, we have to do more. 🙏🏼✨✨✨
•
on oct. 2, i watched the president of the united states mock a woman who had recounted the trauma of being sexually assaulted in front of the world, on live television. and as he did so, a recent poll rattled around my head. the survey found that, while white men regularly supported kavanaugh the most, white women also did so significantly more than hispanic or black people overall. for example, 45% of white women said kavanaugh should be confirmed, compared to 30% of hispanic people and 11% of black people. like so much of these recent weeks, it made me reflect. but even more so, it made me want to write to those women. not lecture them. not denigrate them. just simply to speak to them directly and to try to explain my feelings. this is what i wrote:
•

dear white women who support brett kavanaugh,

last night when i saw donald trump mock dr. christine blasey ford, i couldn’t help focusing on the women behind him who cheered and laughed. i felt like i was falling into a familiar nightmare. it compelled me to reach out to you.
when i was a child my father sexually abused and beat me. my mother did not protect me. she sided with my father, just like these women sided with donald trump, and i understand why. she sided with him because he was the breadwinner. she sided with him because of her need to survive. she sided with him because the reality of what was happening in front of her was so terrible, it was easier not to see.
continued in comments...
#mayaangelou #eveensler #vaginamonologues #sisters #daughters #mothers #standup #useyourvoice #believe #believesurvivors #consciousliving #sanctuary #metoo #women #woman #together #rise #ibelieveher #timesup #scotus

text:
@regran_ed from @thisisnothowmystoryends -  abuse comes in many forms it can be verbal, emotional, mental, financial these are forms of abuse that some people do not recognize right away because they aren’t physical so they are overlooked and you just feel crazy!
.
control, intimidation, isolation, extreme jealousy, monitoring your phone, social media, whereabouts are all forms of abuse and once you allow these to continue it will more than likely escalate to physical abuse. even if it never becomes physical a person who has no respect for your personal boundaries and continually makes you feel like you are not good enough is toxic and abusive and you need to get away from them for your safety and sanity!
.
never hesitate to point out to a friend or family member is you see something that appears to be abusive because often times when you are in it you can’t see it and if they are being mentally abused it’s even more difficult for them to recognize!
.
.
.
.
.
